      <div class="info-box" style="background:#fef3f0;border-left:3px solid #8b1a1a;color:#5a1a1a;margin-bottom:.5rem">
        <strong>Aseptic technique is the dominant procedural safety concern.</strong> Sepsis, epidural abscess, and bacterial meningitis are very rare in absolute terms (&lt;0.01–0.05%) but catastrophic when they occur — and they are the harms most directly modifiable by operator practice. Required: skin antisepsis with chlorhexidine and adequate drying time, sterile drapes and gloves, no-touch technique, and sterile blood collection from a freshly prepared antecubital site. Active infection at the puncture site is an absolute contraindication. Fever, immunocompromise, and multi-attempt placement increase risk.
      </div>
      <div class="info-box">
        <strong>Volume:</strong> 15–20 ml autologous blood via indwelling epidural catheter, injected slowly before catheter removal. &nbsp;
        <strong>Timing:</strong> Immediately after obstetric procedure while catheter is still in situ — evidence strongest within 6 hours of ADP. &nbsp;
        <strong>Monitoring:</strong> Observe for 30 min post-procedure; watch for backache, leg paraesthesia (pressure effect), and any features of fever / meningism that warrant urgent evaluation. &nbsp;
        <strong>Second patch:</strong> If headache develops despite prophylactic EBP, therapeutic EBP is appropriate and not contraindicated. The rate of second patch requirement does not differ significantly between prophylactic and therapeutic groups (Stein 2014: 10% vs 11%).
      </div>
    </div>
