    <!-- CLARIFICATION BLOCK: how to read route-conditional & severity-dependent entries -->
    <div class="content-card" style="background:#fafcfe;border-left:3px solid var(--accent)">
      <div class="card-title" style="color:var(--accent)">Reading these tables — key clarifications</div>
      <div style="font-size:12.5px;line-height:1.6;color:var(--ink-2)">

        <p style="margin-top:0"><strong>1. Accidental dural re-puncture depends on your route.</strong> If you are injecting blood through an <em>in-situ epidural catheter</em>, there is no second needle pass — the re-puncture rate is effectively 0%. If you are placing a <em>fresh Tuohy needle</em> (because the catheter has been removed, or you are patching at a different interspace, or this is a delayed return visit), the published rate is 0.5–1% (Sprigge &amp; Harper 2008; Abouleish; Kokki; Russell 2023). The tool now routes this through the "Planned pEBP route" selector at the top of the page, and the displayed incidence for this complication updates accordingly. Rows that behave this way are marked <span style="font-size:9px;font-family:var(--mono);color:var(--accent);padding:1px 5px;background:var(--accent-light);border-radius:3px">ROUTE-DEPENDENT</span>.</p>

        <p><strong>2. Back pain, radiculopathy, and EBP failure are not route-conditional in this tool.</strong> Published data do not cleanly separate these by route of administration, and the underlying mechanism (epidural blood volume distending the epidural space) is similar whether delivered through needle or catheter. Their weights are therefore held constant. This is a deliberate simplification — you can override any of them with your own estimate using the sliders.</p>

        <p><strong>3. The percentages shown are <em>published incidences</em>, not probabilities for your specific patient.</strong> The "25–35%" on back pain means 25–35% of pEBP recipients in the source cohort developed back pain — not that there is a 25–35% chance for your patient specifically. Use the slider to adjust toward your institutional rate or patient-specific factors.</p>

        <p><strong>4. The "Untreated PDPH" side is probabilistically gated by your PDPH probability.</strong> The complications on the right-hand pan (chronic headache, CVT, subdural haematoma, etc.) only occur if PDPH actually develops. The score therefore scales with your predicted PDPH probability — at 20% probability those complications contribute less to the verdict than at 80%. The formula is documented on the <a href="#" onclick="showTab('methods');return false" style="color:var(--accent)">Methods &amp; scoring</a> tab, §5.</p>

        <p style="margin-bottom:0"><strong>5. Severity is encoded separately from incidence.</strong> A rare-but-severe complication (e.g. CVT &lt;0.5%) carries heavier weight than a common-but-mild one (e.g. back pain 25–35%) despite being 50× less frequent — this is what the <code>baseWeight</code> column captures. Full weighting logic on the Methods tab, §3.</p>

      </div>
    </div>

