      <div class="meth-h">§1 &nbsp;Predicted PDPH probability</div>
      <div class="meth-sub">What the "PDPH probability" slider shows, how the two combination methods work, and why neither is "correct."</div>

      <p style="font-size:12.5px;line-height:1.55">
        Epidemiological <strong>incidence</strong> measures new cases in a population over time — e.g. "PDPH occurs in ~1.5% of all epidural placements." Our tool does not report this. We report a <strong>per-patient posterior probability</strong>, conditional on the accidental dural puncture (ADP) having already occurred. Given ADP with a 17G Tuohy in an obstetric patient, published PDPH rates are 75–85% (Bezov 2010; Sprigge &amp; Harper 2008; Choi 2003). The high-looking 50–80% values the slider produces are therefore expected: the denominator is "patients who have already had an ADP," not "all neuraxial procedures."
      </p>

      <div class="meth-h" style="font-size:12.5px;margin-top:1.2rem;border:none;color:var(--ink-2)">What the model <em>is</em> and what it <em>is not</em></div>
      <p style="font-size:12.5px;line-height:1.55">
        The model is a <strong>modifier-weighted base rate</strong>. A needle-specific base probability is drawn from published ADP cohorts, then adjusted by univariate odds ratios from the literature corresponding to the patient's risk and protective factors. This is a naive-Bayes-style combination of independent univariate effects, not a multivariable logistic regression.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:12.5px;line-height:1.55">
        <strong>No validated multivariable regression model for PDPH-after-ADP exists in the published literature.</strong> Single-cohort regressions have been published (Al-Hashel 2022 Kuwait LP cohort n=285; Agegnehu 2023 orthopedic spinal cohort n=95), but their β coefficients were derived in populations that are demographically and procedurally distinct from yours, with wide confidence intervals (some exceeding 1000-fold) and without external validation. Importing those coefficients into a model you apply to your patients would give the appearance of rigor without the substance. This tool deliberately does not do that.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:12.5px;line-height:1.55">
